| Example: [https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/comeuntochrist/easter/holy-week](https://www.churchofjesuschrist.org/comeuntochrist/easter/holy-week "smart-link")<br><br>Describing the CUC component, any clickable component can trigger a drawer. They do it as 2 components – a tile/button and a drawer that can be attached to any component.<br><br>We will create a new component that can be used to display the closed state as either a button, a button accompanied by some text, or a poster image with a button/link to open the hidden content.<br><br>We will use a 1 column container for what goes in the hidden content section.<br><br>**Figma:**<br><br>[https://www.figma.com/design/XPrhjjI1kJWtfoHlnB0DQv/Friend-Container-Component-Audit?node-id=3975-6886&p=f&t=6nVlMf7NYHUBSnOR-0](https://www.figma.com/design/XPrhjjI1kJWtfoHlnB0DQv/Friend-Container-Component-Audit?node-id=3975-6886&p=f&t=6nVlMf7NYHUBSnOR-0 "smart-link")<br><br>### Front End Requirements<br><br>- On page load, the one column container content is hidden.<br>- If a Title and Description are added, display them according to the Heading Text Alignment setting. The heading text and button are aligned separately so they can either be aligned with each other or on opposite sides of the page.<br>- When an image is added, display it at the set Image Aspect Ratio and at the Component Width setting for the width.<br>- The entire component (image, text area, button/link) is the click target, not just the button or link.<br>- For smaller viewports, stack the button below the text when there is no longer 16px of space between them when next to each other.<br>- If the title or description are long, and the heading text is next to the button, wrap the heading text when it gets within 16px of the button.<br>- The button/link is displayed in the style determined by the Button Style option.<br>- The button is displayed in the color of the Button Style option when Primary or Secondary is the selected button style. (We should be able to use the Theme Colors settings now. If so, we can remove the button color style option. I think.)<br>- If the Add Chevron to Button is set to true, add the down chevron to the button. The down chevron is displayed when the content is hidden. Change the chevron to the up chevron when the content is displayed to show the “drawer” can be closed. if the setting is set to false, do not show any icon.<br>- The background color is applied to the closed button area and only goes to the width of the Component Width setting. This is different than the default edge to edge of background colors but is the standard for 1 column container.<br>- When the button (or any part of the component) is selected, the page content slides down to allow the display of the hidden content. The animation on the content sliding takes about 250ms.<br>- Selecting any part of the original target area will hide the content again and the rest of the page content slides up. Again, 250ms on the animation.<br>- When all the content is displayed, it is also within the background color. The background color area expands when the content is expanded.<br>- The Vertical Spacing setting controls the space between the top of this component and the one above it.<br>- The Title Style setting controls the font and heading tag of the component title.<br>- The Text Overlay Vertical and Text Overlay Horizontal settings control the placement of the Text Overlay content. This field is displayed over the image. Use a Title 1 font. When Text Overlay is applied, add a background shadow over the part of the image where the text will be displayed. Display the text in white. Make sure there is sufficient contrast with the background shadow (3:1 for large text).<br>- Component Width setting controls the width of the component when either closed or open. It limits the width of the content within the hidden one column container.<br>- The Background Color Top and Bottom paddings control the space between the top and bottom of the background color and the top or bottom of the content within the component.<br>- The Hide from In Page Navigation setting controls if the component appears in an in-page navigation when it is added to the page.<br>- Button Alt Text is used as an aria-label for screen readers to explain what the button does.<br><br>- Tech Review: Is this another Style Option? Or is it just the button text?<br><br>### Missed Requirement Detail<br><br>What I failed to state is that when the heading text and the button are aligned the same, the button always goes below the text. If they are aligned on opposite sides, they go next to each other. <br><br>So the header text can be set to Start, Center, or End. The button can be set to Start, Center, or End. <br><br>A Start/Start, Center/Center, or End/End alignment will have the button below the text. <br><br>A Start/End or End/Start will have the button next to the text.<br><br>Any combination with a Center and either Start or End shouldn't be entered by the publisher. That is just bad form, so there is no stated requirement for that. I would say put the button below, just so it does something. <br><br>Please attach screen shots of any strings that are added to property files and send them to Anna Nelson. Translation always asks for context for the strings they are translating.<br><br>### Accessibility considerations<br><br>- Toggle control uses a native <button> with aria-expanded and aria-controls.<br>- Toggle has a clear, descriptive accessible name that updates on state change.<br>- Keyboard access is fully supported (no mouse required).<br>- Focus behavior is predictable: maintained or moved upon expand, restored upon collapse.<br>- All animations must respect prefers-reduced-motion.<br>- Hidden content container has an accessible name via aria-labelledby or aria-label.<br>- HTML must validate and support assistive tech (unique IDs, correct roles, proper nesting).<br><br>### QA Requirements<br><br>- Create an All Options page for this new component.<br>- Create automated tests. |

